# Structs are Value Types

By default, a Struct is incredibly safe. It views its properties as locked down. It refuses to let its own methods change its own properties!

```swift
struct Player {
    var score: Int

    // This will cause a compiler Error!
    func levelUp() {
        score += 10
    }
}
```
Swift will block the code above, saying: "Hey! You're trying to mutate (change) a property inside a normal method!"

# The `mutating` Keyword

To tell Swift that you *intentionally* want a Method to modify the Struct's data, you must label the method with the `mutating` keyword.

```swift
struct Player {
    var score: Int

    // Now it works perfectly!
    mutating func levelUp() {
        score += 10
    }
}
```
Adding `mutating` removes the safety lock and allows the function to change the `score`.

